---

<Layout title="CPF Contribution Rates 2026: Complete Guide by Age Group | SalaryCalculator.sg" description="Comprehensive guide to Singapore CPF contribution rates for 2026 by age group. Covers employee and employer rates, wage ceilings, and graduated PR schedules.">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-gray-500">
    <ol class="flex items-center gap-2">
      <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2 text-gray-900 font-medium">CPF Contribution Rates 2026</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-4xl mx-auto text-gray-700">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">CPF Contribution Rates 2026: Complete Guide by Age Group</h1>

    <p>
      The Central Provident Fund (CPF) is the cornerstone of Singapore's social security system. Established in 1955, the scheme requires mandatory monthly contributions from both employees and employers, creating a financial safety net that covers retirement, housing, healthcare, and education. For 2026, CPF contribution rates remain among the most generous in the region, particularly for younger workers, and understanding exactly how much you and your employer contribute is essential for accurate salary planning.
    </p>

    <p>
      This guide breaks down every aspect of CPF contribution rates for 2026, including the age-based tiers, wage ceilings, graduated Permanent Resident schedules, and practical examples that show exactly how contributions are calculated. Whether you are a fresh graduate starting your first job, a mid-career professional, or approaching retirement, this guide will help you understand what goes into your CPF accounts each month.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">How CPF Contributions Work</h2>

    <p>
      CPF contributions are split between the employee and the employer. The employee's share is deducted from gross monthly wages before the net salary is paid out, while the employer's share is an additional cost borne by the company on top of the gross salary. Both portions are deposited into the employee's CPF accounts. The contribution rates depend on three factors: the employee's age, their residency status (Citizen, PR year 1, PR year 2, or PR year 3 onwards), and whether the wages qualify as ordinary wages or additional wages.
    </p>

    <p>
      Ordinary wages refer to the regular monthly salary, including allowances and commissions that are paid every month. Additional wages include bonuses, annual wage supplements (AWS), leave pay, and other irregular payments. Both types of wages are subject to CPF, but each has its own ceiling that limits the amount on which contributions are calculated.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">CPF Rates for Singapore Citizens and PRs (3rd Year Onwards)</h2>

    <p>
      The following rates apply to Singapore Citizens and Permanent Residents who have been in PR status for three or more years. These are the full rates and represent the standard contribution schedule.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age 55 and Below</h3>
    <p>
      This is the largest group of working Singaporeans. The employee contributes <strong>20%</strong> of ordinary wages, and the employer contributes <strong>17%</strong>, for a combined total of <strong>37%</strong>. For an employee earning the Ordinary Wage ceiling of $6,800 per month, the monthly CPF breakdown is: employee contributes $1,360, employer contributes $1,156, and the total deposited into CPF is $2,516. The employee's take-home pay from the $6,800 is $5,440.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 55 to 60</h3>
    <p>
      At age 55, CPF rates step down. The employee contributes <strong>15%</strong> and the employer contributes <strong>15%</strong>, for a total of <strong>30%</strong>. On a salary of $6,800, the employee's CPF deduction drops to $1,020, giving a take-home pay of $5,780 - $340 more per month than a younger worker earning the same salary. This increase in take-home pay is deliberate, helping workers manage expenses as they approach retirement.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 60 to 65</h3>
    <p>
      The employee rate drops to <strong>9.5%</strong> and the employer rate to <strong>11.5%</strong>, totalling <strong>21%</strong>. On $6,800, the employee contributes $646 and takes home $6,154. The employer contributes $782. This tier reflects the reality that many workers in this age group may be transitioning to part-time work or preparing for full retirement.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 65 to 70</h3>
    <p>
      Employee contribution is <strong>7%</strong> and employer contribution is <strong>9%</strong>, totalling <strong>16%</strong>. On $6,800, the employee contributes $476 and takes home $6,324. The lower rates help maximise disposable income for older workers who may be supplementing their retirement savings with continued employment.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 70</h3>
    <p>
      The lowest tier sees employee contributions of <strong>5%</strong> and employer contributions of <strong>7.5%</strong>, for a total of <strong>12.5%</strong>. On $6,800, the employee contributes $340 and takes home $6,460. Even at this age, contributions continue to build MediSave balances, which are important for healthcare expenses.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">CPF Wage Ceilings for 2026</h2>

    <p>
      CPF contributions are not calculated on unlimited income. Two ceilings apply:
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Ordinary Wage (OW) Ceiling:</strong> The OW ceiling is <strong>$6,800 per month</strong> for 2026. If your monthly ordinary wages exceed $6,800, CPF contributions are calculated only on $6,800. For example, if you earn $10,000 per month, your employee CPF contribution (at age 55 and below) is 20% of $6,800 = $1,360, not 20% of $10,000.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Annual Wage Ceiling:</strong> The total amount of wages subject to CPF in a calendar year is capped at <strong>$102,000</strong>. This ceiling applies to the combination of ordinary wages and additional wages. The Additional Wage (AW) ceiling for any given month is calculated as $102,000 minus the total ordinary wages already subject to CPF for the year. If your annual ordinary wages subject to CPF reach $81,600 (i.e., $6,800 x 12 months), you have an AW ceiling of $20,400 available for bonus CPF contributions.
    </p>

    <p>
      These ceilings mean that very high earners effectively pay a lower percentage of their total income into CPF. A worker earning $20,000 per month will see the same absolute CPF contribution as someone earning $6,800, because contributions are capped at the OW ceiling. This is an important consideration for salary negotiation and total compensation planning.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Graduated CPF Rates for Permanent Residents</h2>

    <p>
      New Permanent Residents do not immediately contribute at the full citizen rates. Instead, a graduated schedule applies during the first two years of PR status. This transition period allows PRs and their employers to adjust to the CPF system gradually.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">PR Year 1 (Full Employer and Graduated Employee - GG Rates)</h3>
    <p>
      In the first year of PR status, the default rates (known as the "GG" rates) for workers aged 55 and below are: employee <strong>5%</strong>, employer <strong>4%</strong>, total <strong>9%</strong>. However, both the employee and employer may jointly elect to contribute at higher rates. Many employers opt for the full employer rate from day one, which would be 17% from the employer side, with the employee still at the graduated 5%.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">PR Year 2 (Full Employer and Graduated Employee - GG Rates)</h3>
    <p>
      In the second year, the default rates for workers aged 55 and below increase to: employee <strong>15%</strong>, employer <strong>9%</strong>, total <strong>24%</strong>. Again, employers and employees may jointly elect to contribute at the full rates. The increased rates bring PRs closer to the citizen contribution levels.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">PR Year 3 Onwards</h3>
    <p>
      From the third year of PR status, contribution rates are identical to those for Singapore Citizens. The employee contributes 20% and the employer 17% for those aged 55 and below, with the same age-based reductions applying to older workers.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Practical Examples</h2>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Example 1: Citizen, Age 30, Monthly Salary $5,000</h3>
    <p>
      Since $5,000 is below the OW ceiling of $6,800, CPF is calculated on the full $5,000. Employee CPF: 20% x $5,000 = $1,000. Employer CPF: 17% x $5,000 = $850. Total CPF: $1,850. Take-home pay: $5,000 - $1,000 = $4,000. The total cost to the employer is $5,000 + $850 = $5,850.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Example 2: Citizen, Age 30, Monthly Salary $12,000</h3>
    <p>
      Since $12,000 exceeds the OW ceiling of $6,800, CPF is calculated on $6,800. Employee CPF: 20% x $6,800 = $1,360. Employer CPF: 17% x $6,800 = $1,156. Total CPF: $2,516. Take-home pay: $12,000 - $1,360 = $10,640. Note that the employee retains the full amount above $6,800 without further CPF deductions.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Example 3: PR Year 1, Age 28, Monthly Salary $6,000</h3>
    <p>
      Under the default GG rates for PR year 1, the employee contributes 5% and the employer 4%. Employee CPF: 5% x $6,000 = $300. Employer CPF: 4% x $6,000 = $240. Total CPF: $540. Take-home pay: $6,000 - $300 = $5,700. Compare this to a citizen at the same salary who would take home $4,800 - the PR year 1 employee keeps $900 more per month but has significantly less going into CPF savings.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Why CPF Rates Matter for Your Career</h2>

    <p>
      Understanding CPF rates is not just an academic exercise. The rates directly affect your monthly budget, your housing affordability (since OA funds can be used for HDB and private property purchases), your retirement adequacy, and your healthcare coverage through MediSave. Employers also factor CPF into their total compensation budgets, which means the employer CPF contribution is part of your real compensation even though it does not appear in your bank account each month.
    </p>

    <p>
      When comparing job offers, particularly between roles that offer different base salaries and bonus structures, it is important to consider how CPF ceilings affect each offer. A higher base salary above the OW ceiling does not attract additional employer CPF, while a lower base salary with a larger bonus might generate more total CPF if the bonus pushes your additional wages into the AW ceiling.
    </p>

    <p>
      For workers approaching 55, the upcoming reduction in CPF rates represents a meaningful increase in take-home pay. Planning for this transition - including adjusting savings rates and reviewing housing loan repayments that use OA funds - is an important part of pre-retirement financial planning.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Changes to CPF Rates Over the Years</h2>

    <p>
      CPF rates have been adjusted numerous times since the fund's inception in 1955. The most significant recent change was the gradual increase in contribution rates for older workers announced in Budget 2023, with increases phased in from 2024 to 2026. These increases are designed to help older Singaporeans build larger retirement savings as the population ages and life expectancy increases. The rates for workers aged 55 to 60, for example, were raised from 28.5% total in 2023 to 30% in 2026, and rates for workers above 60 saw similar step-ups.
    </p>

    <p>
      Looking ahead, the government has signalled its intention to continue supporting adequate retirement savings through CPF. While future rate changes are not confirmed, the trend has been towards maintaining or gradually increasing rates, particularly for older workers, to ensure retirement adequacy in a society with increasing longevity.
    </p>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What is the maximum CPF contribution for employees aged 55 and below in 2026?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          For Singapore Citizens and PRs (3rd year onwards) aged 55 and below, the employee contributes 20% and the employer contributes 17% of ordinary wages, capped at the Ordinary Wage ceiling of $6,800 per month. The maximum monthly employee CPF contribution is therefore $1,360, and the maximum employer contribution is $1,156, for a combined maximum of $2,516 per month from ordinary wages alone.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Do CPF contribution rates change when I turn 55?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          Yes. CPF rates decrease at ages 55, 60, 65, and 70. When you turn 55, the total rate drops from 37% to 30% (employee from 20% to 15%, employer from 17% to 15%). The reduction is designed to increase your take-home pay as you approach retirement. You will also become eligible to withdraw some CPF savings above the Full Retirement Sum at age 55.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What is the CPF Annual Wage ceiling for 2026?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The CPF Annual Wage ceiling is $102,000 for 2026. This cap applies to the total ordinary wages and additional wages (such as bonuses) subject to CPF in a calendar year. If your total ordinary wages subject to CPF for the year are $81,600 (i.e., $6,800 x 12), then up to $20,400 of additional wages can also attract CPF contributions.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>

